You&#39;re calling `.Result()` in the same loop:

    for (i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
        sc[i] = new Score();
        sc[i].data(i+1);
        sc[i].calScore();
        sc[i].Result(i+1);
    }

If what you want instead is to re-start from the beginning and call `.Result()` in a new loop, then what you want is two loops:

    for (i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
        sc[i] = new Score();
        sc[i].data(i+1);
        sc[i].calScore();
    }

    for (i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
        sc[i].Result(i+1);
    }

Try to call the `Result` method in the second loop
```java
    Score[] sc = new Score[n];
    for (i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
        sc[i] = new Score();
        sc[i].data(i+1);
        sc[i].calScore();
    }

    for (i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
        sc[i].Result(i+1);
    }
```

In the first loop you will read and compute all data, and in the second one you will only print the `System.out.println`

